— Want me to fill in for you?
— No, Ben.

03:32.671 --> 03:36.038
I believe l'll fulfill my obligation for today.

03:37.551 --> 03:40.042
— Sorry.
— (Chuckles) No worries.

03:40.179 --> 03:42.135
I'm not one of those militant ex—smokers.

03:42.264 --> 03:45.597
— It's good you quit.
— Because of my size?

03:45.726 --> 03:48.968
Yeah, tobacco would be
one more bullet in the chamber.

03:49.105 --> 03:51.096
Shall we?

03:53.401 --> 03:55.892
This book is really old.

03:56.028 --> 03:57.529
(Cray) Yes, it is.

03:57.655 --> 04:00.692
But The Awakening's human concerns
are as relevant today

04:00.825 --> 04:03.737
as they were at the end of the 19th century.

04:03.869 --> 04:05.325
Hey, at least it's short.

04:05.454 --> 04:07.319
(Ben) Yeah, thank you, Professor Bernette.

04:07.456 --> 04:09.287
— (Laughter)
— (Cray) True.

04:09.417 --> 04:12.409
So I want you to take your time with it.

04:12.545 --> 04:16.663
Pay attention to the language itself,
the ideas.

04:16.799 --> 04:19.882
Don't think in terms
of a beginning and an end,

04:20.010 --> 04:22.922
because unlike some plot—driven entertainments,

04:23.055 --> 04:26.218
there is no closure in real life,

04:26.350 --> 04:28.432
not really.

04:28.561 --> 04:32.019
You said that all books are about a problem that the
protagonist has to solve.

04:32.148 --> 04:35.640
Or a quest.
The protagonist is looking for something.

04:35.776 --> 04:38.563
